Sentencas: Feeding solid oxide fuel cells (SOFCs) with gas from biomass gasification is promising with regard to highly efficient power generation.
Titulo: Coupling SOFCs to biomass gasification - The influence of phenol on cell degradation in simulated bio-syngas. Part I: Electrochemical analysis

Sentencas: But it is also intricate since biogenic contaminants are harmful to state-of-the-art anode materials.
Titulo: Coupling SOFCs to biomass gasification - The influence of phenol on cell degradation in simulated bio-syngas. Part I: Electrochemical analysis

Sentencas: In this work the influence of phenol as a biogenic model contaminant on the performance of single solid oxide fuel cells was studied under realistic conditions.
Titulo: Coupling SOFCs to biomass gasification - The influence of phenol on cell degradation in simulated bio-syngas. Part I: Electrochemical analysis

Sentencas: For this purpose Ni/YSZ anode supported cells were operated with simulated bio-syngas, applying an electrical load of 0.34 A/cm(2).
Titulo: Coupling SOFCs to biomass gasification - The influence of phenol on cell degradation in simulated bio-syngas. Part I: Electrochemical analysis

Sentencas: Over a duration of several hundreds of hours phenol was periodically added to the fuel gas.
Titulo: Coupling SOFCs to biomass gasification - The influence of phenol on cell degradation in simulated bio-syngas. Part I: Electrochemical analysis

Sentencas: The tests showed that for the lowest concentration of phenol no accelerated degradation could be observed regarding cell potential and electrical impedance measurements, but disintegration of the Ni/YSZ support took place.
Titulo: Coupling SOFCs to biomass gasification - The influence of phenol on cell degradation in simulated bio-syngas. Part I: Electrochemical analysis

Sentencas: Metal dusting of the anode support was found to be the most important mechanism of degradation.
Titulo: Coupling SOFCs to biomass gasification - The influence of phenol on cell degradation in simulated bio-syngas. Part I: Electrochemical analysis
